    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become connected in such a way that their properties, like spin or energy, are correlated, even when they're separated by large distances. This means that if something happens to one particle, it instantly affects the state of the other entangled particles, regardless of distance. The key difference from classical correlation is that entanglement can't be explained by classical notions like cause-and-effect, and it happens instantly across space, defying time and space constraints. In essence, entanglement blurs the lines between space and time, and our understanding of how particles interact.",
